mention.text: thou That cool ' st the twilight of the sultry day

I alone -- a thousand blossoms round Inhale thee in the fulness of delight ; And languid forms rise up , and pulses bound Livelier , at coming of the wind of night ; And , languishing to hear thy grateful sound , Lies the vast inland
The shutting flower , and darkling waters pass , And where the o'ershadowing branches
they who stand about the sick man 's bed , Shall joy to listen to thy distant sweep , And softly part his curtains to allow Thy visit
the circle of eternal change , Which is the life of nature
